    "narrative": "**Corbin Carroll** headline today\u2019s slate with an elite efficiency score of 85.94, capitalizing on a soft matchup against Martin and a favorable slotting at the number three hole. He is our primary engine for stolen base production today, and the projection model rewards him heavily for his superior xwOBA metrics. Similarly, **Mickey Moniak** provides excellent value at 75.98; he benefits from the most pronounced park factor (+14%) and faces the highest xERA starter of the day, Waldron, creating an ideal environment for his aggressive profile. **Jose Caballero** also serves as a high-upside play (67.92), as his dynamic platoon edge against the lefty Tolle helps him overcome a lower spot in the batting order to remain a \"Strong\" start.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Brice Turang**, who sat just outside the starting threshold with a 46.56 score. While **Brice Turang** provides the necessary speed our roster craves, the optimizer penalized him heavily due to a daunting matchup against Skubal, whose elite skill set\u2014specifically his ability to suppress production\u2014made the risk of wasting a game cap too high compared to the high-floor output expected from **Giancarlo Stanton** or **Austin Riley**. Elsewhere, we are exercising caution with **James Wood** and **Seiya Suzuki**; both face sub-3.10 xERA arms, and despite **Seiya Suzuki** benefiting from a slight wind advantage, their sub-52 efficiency scores confirm they are fringe plays that require close monitoring of early at-bats.\n\nWe are avoiding the \"Below Floor\" trap entirely, keeping **Dalton Rushing** and **Alex Freeland** on the bench as both struggled against the projection constraints presented by Webb. With **Josh Naylor** inactive due to a team off-day, we are relying on the established reliability of **Austin Riley** and **Trevor Story** to anchor the middle of the order. While we maintain exposure to speed via **Jose Caballero** and **Corbin Carroll**, keep an eye on the late-inning developments for **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**; his score is dragged down by a bottom-third batting order assignment, but his ability to flip a category on a single steal attempt remains a constant factor in our daily risk assessment.",
